    value: 지순(至順)은 원(元)나라 문종(文宗)의 연호인데, 그 기간이 3년까지 밖에 되지 않는다. 그러므로 여기의 지순 9년은 잘못 적은 것이다. 또 《고려사》열전에 의하면 최안도는 충혜왕(忠惠王)초에 감찰어사가 되었다고 하였으며, 충혜왕 원년이 지순 2년에 해당하는 것인 즉, 여기의 지순 9년은 실은 지순 원년이며 충숙왕 17년으로 보여진다.
english:
  title: Epitaph for Eunuch Choi
  author: Choi Hae
  language: eng
  text: |-
    My nature inclines toward idleness and cowardice in confrontation. I recall, some ten years past, when I was falsely accused by a favored eunuch of the king. Though slothful by disposition, I could not help but visit him once. At that time, all the renowned gentlemen and officials gathered in the outer chambers, and his gates thronged like a marketplace. When the eunuch finally appeared, the visitors rushed to bow and bend their knees, each fearing to be last. I thought such conduct unbecoming of a scholar and wished to greet him with proper courtesy, yet the eunuch regarded me with contempt, mounted his horse, and departed without so much as a glance. Ashamed and resentful, I withdrew, saying to myself: "This matter was born of misunderstanding. What harm is there in having no vindication?" Later, I heard that Eunuch Choi held daily audience with the king, and his counsel was never refused—he had earned great renown. Someone urged me to seek him out and lay bare my case. So I waited by the gate, and when Eunuch Choi glimpsed me among the crowd, he specially descended from his seat to greet me first, inquiring my purpose. There I spoke the whole truth. Though the eunuch's influence was then at its height and suppressing it proved most difficult, the matter came to nothing. Yet I was moved by Eunuch Choi's magnanimity in receiving a scholar and listening to his words—there was in him an ancient spirit of righteousness. From that time forward, whenever I visited, I received uncommon courtesy.

    Eunuch Choi served our kingdom, and had he served at the imperial court, he would have held rank of the third degree. Now that he has suddenly passed, how could I not mourn him? It is fitting that I accept the trust of his son, record the deeds of his life in sequence, and compose this epitaph to express my sorrow.

    The Master's name was An-do; his family name was Choi. His childhood name was Na-hae. His ancestors were from Haeju, but later settled in Yongju and took their residence there. The genealogy of his forebears is too distant to trace. His great-grandfather, named Gwang, served as Vice-Director of Households. His grandfather, named Dae-bu, first entered service as Inspecting General. His father, named Hyeon, served as Magnanimous and Upright Grand Master, Inspecting Censor in Chief, and Senior General Guardian.

    Through the Master's prominence, the court granted his father the posthumous rank of Court Petitioner and Vice-Commandant of the Great Capital Route, with the title Marquis of Daxing County. His mother, Lady Kim, received the posthumous title Marchioness of Daxing County.

    In the first year of Zhiyuan, when the Master was fifteen years old, he was selected from the unranked officials to become a Military Commander. In the fourth year of Yanyou, he was appointed Commander of the Guard with the rank of Court Ceremony Master, and was granted the purple vestments. Through successive promotions, he rose to Senior General Guardian. After three transfers, he attained the rank of Grand Master of Proper Conduct.

    In the fourth year of Taiding, he took command of the Eagle and Yang Army as Judge of Military Records. In the ninth year of Zhishun, he was promoted to Vice-Director of the Secretariat with the rank of Deputy Keeper of the Heir Apparent. Shortly thereafter, he was transferred to Censor and concurrent Director of the Secretariat, receiving the title "Collaborator in Harmonious Counsel and Allied Virtue Merit Official." He also received imperial appointment as Auxiliary Commissioner of the Left and Right Bureaus of the Zhendong Provincial Secretariat. Two years later, upon imperial mandate, he entered the court to serve as Personal Attendant. In the first year of Yuantong, he was specially appointed Minister of the Imperial Household with the rank of Counselor for Court Deliberation.

    In the second year of Zhiyuan, he was transferred to become Vice-Director of the Imperial Granary with the rank of Court Petitioner. In the sixth year, he was again transferred to serve as Director of the Imperial Granary with the rank of Counselor of the Inner Court. Throughout nine years of service in the capital, he was promoted three times and twice received imperial decrees that brought honor to our kingdom—first in the third year of Zhishun, and again in the fifth year of Zhiyuan.

    The following spring, having completed his duties and prepared to return home, he fell gravely ill. After seven days, he passed from this world at the age of forty-seven, on the twenty-seventh day of the third month in the year Gengchen.

    The Master was gifted from youth. Following his father, the Court Petitioner, he served the Supreme General and Prince of Shen at the royal residence in the capital, and thus came to speak the languages of three nations. Appointed to royal service, he labored long in faithful attendance. For his diligence, he was granted one hundred plots of land and ten servants. During the years of Zhizhi, when his former sovereign faced slander at court, the Master remained steadfast in his loyalty, unwavering. He received two hundred plots of land and twenty servants as reward.

    In the early years of Taiding, when the imperial court considered establishing the Zhendong Provincial Secretariat according to precedent, the Master, together with the late Prime Minister Kim Yi and others, argued strenuously against it and succeeded in preventing its establishment. For this service, he received one hundred plots of land and ten servants.

    When the young successor took the throne, the Master was suddenly appointed to the Secretariat, becoming indispensable in the ruler's trust and reliance. Furthermore, during the years of Zhishun, when the present sovereign was at sea, much of the provisions for his needs came from the Master's own resources. When the sovereign later ascended to full power, his rewards were most generous. The Master received an imperial rescript whereby all his lands and property became inviolable—none dared encroach upon them. Thus was his position at court truly established. Looking upon these deeds, one may well perceive the Master's character; there is naught else to say.

    His wife, Lady Gu, was the daughter of the late Deputy Keeper of the Heir Apparent, named Ye. Through the Master's eminence, she received the title Marchioness of Boling. They had four sons and four daughters. The eldest son, named Reo, now holds the rank of Senior General Guardian. The second, named Won, is now a General Guardian. The third is named Suk-sin, and the fourth is named Mun-gu; none as yet have taken office. The eldest daughter married the former General Guardian In-dang. The second married the former Military Commander Kim Yu-on. The third married the former Squadron Commander Lim Hui-jae. The youngest remains unmarried. In the fifth month of this year, the Master was laid to rest in accordance with proper rites.

    The Epitaph speaks thus:

    To serve a kingdom as that kingdom's subject,
    To serve the Son of Heaven as his subject—
    What reckoning of weightier and lesser can I make of such distinctions in my own person?

    Ancient wisdom tells: one may be a scholar of a single realm,
    Yet also a scholar of all under heaven.
    Without talents that encompass both,
    Who could achieve such a thing?

    Alas! Though wisdom may stretch long,
    Years are granted but briefly.
    The world's affairs cannot be trusted—
    Is this not heaven's will?
    Is this not heaven's will?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The narrative opening recounts the author's personal encounter with a high-ranking eunuch and his subsequent relationship with Choi An-do, establishing the memorial's emotional foundation through the contrast between two models of conduct and influence.
  - key: ''
    value: The epitaph form (following the biographical narrative) was a standard literary genre in classical East Asian writing, combining genealogical records, official achievements, and moral assessment into verse and reflective prose.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'three nations' languages' reflects the multilingual competence required of court officials during the Yuan Dynasty, when the Mongol empire encompassed diverse conquered territories.
